<p><i><b>The Fog of War: Eleven Lessons from the Life of Robert S. McNamara</b></i> (2003), directed by <a href="/wiki/Errol_Morris" title="Errol Morris">Errol Morris</a>, is an American <a href="/wiki/Documentary_film" title="Documentary film">documentary film</a> about the life and times of former <a href="/wiki/United_States_Secretary_of_Defense" title="United States Secretary of Defense">U.S. Secretary of Defense</a> <a href="/wiki/Robert_S._McNamara" title="Robert S. McNamara" class="mw-redirect">Robert S. McNamara</a>. The original score is by <a href="/wiki/Philip_Glass" title="Philip Glass">Philip Glass</a>.</p>
<p>The film is a composite interview of McNamara, detailing his life between 1961 and 1968, and the difficult career decisions he took in that time. <i>The Fog of War</i> title denotes battlefield uncertainty during the fighting. It won the <a href="/wiki/76th_Academy_Awards" title="76th Academy Awards">Academy Award</a> for <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Documentary_Feature" title="Academy Award for Documentary Feature" class="mw-redirect">Best Documentary Feature</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Independent_Spirit_Award_for_Best_Documentary_Feature" title="Independent Spirit Award for Best Documentary Feature">Independent Spirit Award for Best Documentary Feature</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-NY_Times_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NY_Times-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
